results.notes:
Sarcogyne species with epilithic, white, rimose-areolate thallus that I would characterize as farinose. Thallus seems to be ~0.2-0.3 mm thick, with +/- continuous algal layer but otherwise without much layer differentiation. Cortex indistinct. Lecideine apothecia slightly raised above thallus and appearing white-pruinose, with a thin raised rim. Apothecia irregular in shape, emerging from thallus areoles. Larger areoles approaching 1mm diam., larger apothecia ~0.5mm diam.

Micro: hymenium over 100 micrometers tall, exciple margin dark brown, of +/- oval cells at the margins, ~60-70 micrometers thick at the top. Epihymenium reddish-brown, hymenium hyaline, subhymenium/hypothecium slightly darker in color.

Spores seem quite large for a Sarcogyne: 7.5×2.3, 8.5×2.6, 7.4×2.4, 7.3×2.6, 7.0×2.8, 7.2×2.8, 8.0×3.2 micrometers. I measured the larger-appearing spores in my fields of view because I worried that smaller-looking spores might just be immature or rotated in a way that made them seem smaller.

Chemistry: thallus and apothecia C-, K-, KC-. Appears to be UV- as well.

results.notes:
Macro:thallus of small, brown, convex areoles, smooth and slightly shiny under dissecting scope. Areoles sometimes with multiple apothecia, apothecia darker brown than thallus, flush with thallus surface to slightly immersed when young. No sign of parathecial crown. In areoles with multiple apos, it looks like they are often in the process of dividing into multiple areoles. Areole margins turn inward to an attachment point, lower surface light in color.

Micro: no expanded parathecium, indistinct at margin, ~15-20 micrometers wide. Hymenium height hard to determine, but I think it’s around 80-90 micrometers. Hymenium hemiamyloid (turning reddish in Lugol’s). Cortex ~20 micrometers thick.

Chemistry: K- and C- thallus in section

Spores: ~5-7 × 2-3 micrometers
